Whether your current tank water heater is nearing the end of its service life or you want to upgrade to have the latest, most-efficient technology in your home, there are plenty of reasons these days to go with a TANKLESS WATER HEATER. While there are many tankless water heater brands on the market today, one of our favorites is Noritz. If you want to take advantage of the benefits of tankless water heaters, along with the best technology and 25-year warranty available, Noritz tankless units are excellent options. Call All American Plumbing, Heating & Air to learn more about the advantages of Noritz tankless water heaters and explore your best options for installation. What Are Tankless Water Heaters? Tankless water heaters are essentially a way to provide hot water on demand. Unlike conventional tank-style water heaters, they don’t store heated water in a tank waiting for you to use it; instead, the unit heats the water up as needed, making them great energy-saving options and allowing you to enjoy near-instant hot water! Benefits Of Tankless Water Heaters More Energy-Efficient And Cost Less to Operate Tankless water heaters are much more energy-efficient than traditional storage tank models and can lower your monthly utility bills significantly. This is because they only heat the water when you need it instead of constantly heating a large quantity of water in a storage tank. Heats Water on Demand Tankless water heaters don’t waste energy storing hot water, but instead, heat the water as needed. This means you will never run out of hot water and need to wait for it to reheat. Smaller Unit That Saves Floor Space on Your Home Tankless water heater units take up much less space than traditional tank models, making them ideal for small spaces or homes where space is limited. Unlimited Hot Water (Doesn’t Run Out) As mentioned previously, tankless water heaters provide an unlimited supply of hot water on demand without the need to wait for it to reheat after running out. Typically Last Longer Than Tank Units Noritz and other tankless models typically have a much longer lifespan than traditional tank versions. While traditional tank water heaters last for up to 12 years, tankless models can last up to 20 years with proper maintenance. Why We Recommend Noritz Tankless Water Heaters At ALL AMERICAN PLUMBING, we’re proud to offer Noritz tankless water heaters to our customers in the Central Valley. Why do we recommend Noritz? For starters, they pioneered water heaters for over 60 years and were the first to introduce electronically controlled tankless units back in 1981. Today, Nortiz accounts for about 70% of tankless products in the world, making it the largest global manufacturer. Noritz products also come with the best tankless water heater warranty in the business – up to 25 years. This incredible warranty gives you peace of mind and protects your investment in your home. Noritz EZ Series Two of the most popular tankless water systems that we install come from Noritz’s innovative EZ Series. These units can be retrofitted when replacing a traditional tank water heater. This makes installation much quicker, easier, and more economical. We can often use your existing plumbing, gas line, and venting. Depending on the size of your home and water usage, there are a few different models to choose from, including: EZTR50 – Replaces 40- to 50-gallon tank water heaters, which is typically suitable for homes with 1-2 bathrooms. This model offers 9.8 gallons per minute. EZTR75 – Replaces 75-gallon tanks for larger homes. Offers 11.1 gallons per minute Tankless Water Heater Installation In The Central Valley For a consultation and estimate to install a Noritz tankless water heater in your home, call the expert team of ALL AMERICAN PLUMBING, HEATING & AIR at (209) 509-4448. We’ll evaluate your needs and talk through the best options to keep you supplied with all the hot water you need. We look forward to hearing from you! While not ideal, it isn’t necessarily a reason to panic if your tap water looks rusty. Common causes of rusty tap water include a water main break, water heater issues, or corroding metal water pipes. By following clues of how widespread and from which faucets the issue appears, you can narrow down and find the root cause. While some homeowners are able to troubleshoot and resolve the issue on their own, if you have any doubts or fears, it’s always best to consult a licensed plumber. The team at All American Plumbing, Heating & Air is available to help you investigate and fix any rusty water problems. Give us a call today, and we’ll be happy to answer any questions you may have! Is Rusty Water Safe? If you’re wondering if rusty-colored water is safe to bathe in, the answer is usually yes. A slight discoloration in water does not indicate a health risk. Additionally, if your rusty tap water is hard, it may be bad for your hair. Hard water also makes it harder for soap to lather and as a result, it takes longer to get clean. While rusty water is generally safe to drink, it can discolor items like clothing and dishes. The rust particles are usually iron oxide, which is a result of corroding metal pipes. Iron oxide is not toxic and won’t harm your health. However, if the water has an unpleasant odor or taste, you should get it tested for bacteria or other contaminants immediately. However, if your rusty water contains lead or arsenic, which is not common, it is best to avoid drinking the water altogether. You can have your water tested by a professional or purchase a DIY testing kit to check for contaminants such as lead. Top Reasons Your Tap Water Looks Rusty By understanding the potential causes of rusty tap water and taking steps to investigate further, you can determine whether you need to take action. Read on to find out the three main reasons your water might be looking rusty. If Both Your Hot And Cold Water Is Brown… For instances where your hot and cold water are both appearing brown from the faucet, the reason is likely from a water main break in a local water main or fire hydrant. Water main breaks can result in sediment in your water supply due to the interconnectedness of many municipality water lines. This happens often and is typically not a major cause for concern. If both your hot and cold water is running with brown residue or sediment, check your local “boil water warnings” to see if it’s a widespread issue. If not, alert the local water authority as soon as possible to make them aware of the problem and ask if there has been any recent maintenance on the water mains in your area. This should give you a good indication of what is causing the issue as well as a better idea of how long it will take until your water supply is running clear again. If Only The Hot Water Is Brown… If your hot water is brown and the cold water supply looks clear, your water heater is likely to blame. Sediment buildup in the water heater itself can lead to rusty brown water. This problem should be eradicated as soon as possible to prevent your water heater from breaking entirely. Sediment buildup can lead to premature corrosion in the water tank, along with the potential for problematic leaks, cracks, and even bursts/explosions within the tank. To fix the problem, you will need to drain and flush the water heater tank in order to remove any sediment buildup. (This should be done at least annually or every six months if you have a hard water supply.) If it’s too late and you notice the water heater tank is showing early signs of corrosion, call in a plumber for their professional opinion on what to do next. If You Only Notice The Issue From A Few Faucets… For specific faucets with sediment buildup or rusty water, you likely have a water supply pipe that is corroding. Many homes with older plumbing systems suffer from sediment buildup in the pipes. Sometimes this can be a minor problem, easily fixed by running the water for 20 minutes or so to flush out any small amounts of rust that might have broken loose from the pipes. However, if the problem persists after attempting a simple fix, you likely need to replace the pipes in question. Better To Be Safe Than Sorry In any case, it’s important to exercise caution when dealing with rusty water or sediment in your water supply. Switch to drinking bottled or boiled water for the time being until you can get the problem solved. Contact The Experts For a Diagnosis of The Problem It’s also a good idea to bring in an experienced plumber to make sure your drinking water is as clean as possible. If you’re concerned about the color or taste of your water, call All American Plumbing, Heating & Air today at (209) 509-4448. The best way to do this is to schedule a professional inspection and cleaning every three months. However, this is something you can also do on your own. In this article, we’ll look at the steps you must take to ensure the filter is properly cleaned. All American Plumbing, Heating & Air is your one-stop-shop for all things heating and cooling related. Our experienced technicians use the latest tools and techniques to provide you with exceptional HVAC services. From installation to repairs and maintenance, we have you covered. Why Do You Need Air Filters? Your HVAC system’s air filter is designed to trap dirt, dust, pollen, and other particles that can cause health hazards in your home. This filter also helps minimize energy consumption by allowing the system to run more efficiently. A dirty air filter makes it harder for the system to blow air through the house and causes it to work less effectively. Why Clean Your Air Filters? Cleaning your HVAC air filter is essential to keeping your home comfortable, energy-efficient, and safe from allergens and other air contaminants. Depending on the type of filter, you can either replace it periodically or clean it yourself. Types of Air Filters No matter the type of HVAC system you have, the type of air filter used in your system may be one of those listed below. Fiberglass Filters Basic, disposable fiberglass filters are intended to guard your HVAC system against dust and debris, they offer minimal air quality benefits. UV Filters Utilizing a UV filter can eradicate viruses and bacteria in your home’s central air system, keeping you safe from potentially harmful germs. Electrostatic Filters Harnessing electrostatic power, these filters magnetically draw particles and dust from the atmosphere. HEPA Filters These filters are particularly adept at blocking out pollutants, making them perfect for those with serious respiratory difficulties. Pleated Filters With its pleats, this filter allows for an expanded surface area that successfully captures more pollutants. Washable Filters Although these filters may be more expensive than other options, you’ll save money in the long run since they can be easily disassembled and cleaned. However, they should be replaced once they begin to show signs of damage. How to Clean an HVAC Filter Whether you choose to replace or clean your air filter, here are the steps you should take to ensure a thorough job: Step 1: Turn Off Your HVAC System Before you begin, make sure to switch off your HVAC system. This will help ensure that the filter is not damaged by any debris or dust in the air while it’s being cleaned. Step 2: Find The Service Panel The service panel is located somewhere in the system’s air conditioning unit. Find it and locate the filter. You should also check the unit’s vents as some units have several filters. Step 3: Remove And Clean The Filter Once you’ve found the filter, take it out and place it on the floor facing up. Then vacuum it to remove any dust or debris. Step 4: Further Clean The Filter If step 3 doesn’t do the trick, you can use any of the three ways to get a better clean. To clean a mildly soiled HVAC filter, set it in your sink or bathtub and give it a good rinse with warm running water. Alternatively, when cleaning your filter, you can use a garden hose for an efficient job. However, remember to avoid any pressurized settings because they could damage the filter! If you require a more thorough cleanse, fill your sink with a combination of one part vinegar and one part warm water. Allow the filter to rest in this solution for an hour before rinsing thoroughly. To wrap up, gently remove any remaining residue with your hands or a soft brush. Step 5: Reinstall The Filter Once the filter is completely dry, replace it in its original position and make sure that it is seated snugly. Then, turn on your HVAC unit and check if the filter is working properly. If it isn’t, you may need to replace it or contact a professional for assistance. Cleaning your air filter regularly can help prolong your HVAC system’s life by providing clean air to circulate. Doing so can also keep your home safe from any allergens or contaminants, allowing you to breathe easily. That said, make sure to follow the steps outlined above for a successful clean and stay on top of regular maintenance! Do You Need Help Replacing or Cleaning Your HVAC Filter? If you need help changing and cleaning your HVAC filter, contact the professionals at All American Plumbing, Heating & Air. There’s no exception when it comes to your bathrooms and kitchen—the busiest rooms in the home as far as plumbing is concerned! Both are subject to drain clogs from soap scum in the bathroom to FOG (fats, oils, and grease) in the kitchen. Your bathroom plumbing and kitchen plumbing are essential to the overall functionality of your home, and therefore when you’re looking for experienced plumbers and you need a team you can trust—give us a call! We’ve been in the business of drain and sewer cleaning, among other comprehensive plumbing services, since 2001, and we’re eager to show you how we work “In the types Service of Excellence.” Schedule your first appointment by calling our team today at (209) 509-4448 or use our online form. Common Types of Drain and Sewer Problems Many homeowners live with drain and sewer problems longer than they should, simply because they aren’t aware of the warning signs. Common types of drain problems include slow drains, frequent or recurring clogs, foul odor coming from your drains, and water flooding below sinks or surrounding drains. Sewer problems include gurgling toilets, drains that are slow to clear, and strong sewer odor – along with more intense issues such as cracked walls, pest invasions indoors, and sewage backup in the toilet or tub. If you notice any of these signs, it’s time to call All American Sewer & Drain for professional help! What Causes Clogged Drains? There are a few different things that can create this issue. Whatever the nature of the problem ends up being, it requires the right tools and training to successfully unclog a drain and keep it clean. But what scenarios lead to these clogs? It’s dependent on where the drain is, first off, but we’ve listed a few common causes of clogged drains below: Hair in the Bathroom Drains: When you shower or style your hair over your sink, some of your hair is bound to wind up in the drain, creating clogs deep within the pipes. FOG in the Kitchen Drains: FOG stands for fats, oils, and grease. The problem with these substances is that they harden as they cool, and eventually create stubborn clogs. Tree Roots: The smallest of leaks from your sewer line or main water line can quickly attract growing tree roots, which constantly seek out sources of water. Bathroom Drain Cleaning Services There’s nothing quite like a clogged bathroom drain. It’s a “hairy” situation, and you don’t have to deal with it alone! All American Sewer & Drain provides comprehensive bathroom drain cleaning services including sink and tub drains as well as toilet clogs and leaky pipes. Before you attempt to clear a stubborn clog, give one of the experienced professional plumbers at All American Sewer & Drain a call. We can safely and efficiently remove the obstruction without damaging your drain or surrounding pipes. Learn more about our bathroom drain cleaning services by giving us a call. Kitchen Drain Cleaning Services You would be surprised to learn about the variety of objects we have discovered clogging up a kitchen drain: jewelry, plastic toys, food particles, paper products and more! If you have a clog somewhere in your kitchen plumbing, it can wreak havoc in your daily routine. If you are in need of kitchen drain cleaning services, All American Sewer & Drain can help. We are experts when it comes to removing the largest objects from kitchen drains without damaging your pipes, sink, or countertop. We are confident you’ll love the work we do. Give us a call! How Do You Unclog a Drain? For effective sewer drain cleaning, let alone sink drain or shower drain cleaning, you need a lot more than a store-bought drain cleanser. In fact, these solutions can actually cause more harm than good as they’re corrosive and can slowly eat away at your plumbing system. Professional drain snaking is typically the best bet, and hydro-jetting may be needed for the most stubborn of clogs. Don’t hesitate to contact us for our reliable drain cleaning services. Hydro-jetting involves the use of highly pressurized water to scour the interior of your pipes. It’s an environmentally friendly process, and there aren’t any harsh or corrosive chemicals to deal with that could compromise your plumbing. We feed a hose with a special nozzle into the line and then use that pressurized water to blast away any blockages. This method is so effective that it prevents further clogs from forming, so long as you properly care for and maintain your plumbing system. Quick Tips – Recover Jewelry Lost in Drain Ask About Our Sewer Drain Cleaning Warranty Sewer line cleaning is not something you should attempt on your own, nor is it something you should try to perform on your own. Our highly trained and experienced plumbers not only effectively clean all of your sewer drains, but we can check to ensure that no breaches have occurred—such as the infiltration of tree roots. The good news is, if we do find damaged sewer lines, we can access and repair the sewer line via trenchless technology, rather than tearing up part of your property. We are so confident in our sewer cleaner services that we provide a 1-year warranty for up to two stoppages in your main sewer line. Give us a call today for more details! We also offer a 6-year complete warranty on all plumbing work except fixtures available to our AMP club maintenance program members. We provide drain and sewer services in Los Banos, Turlock, Merced, Patterson, and the Central Valley Area. Schedule an appointment with our drain cleaning experts by calling us at (209) 509-4448. You may need hydro jetting to get the job done right. Our plumbers have the experience necessary to operate hydro jetting machinery. With these powerful jets, All American Sewer & Drain can blast your drains clear of blockages and build up. Schedule your first appointment by calling our team today at (209) 509-4448 or use our online form. We are proud to serve customers in Los Banos, Turlock, Merced, Patterson, and the surrounding Central Valley areas. What is Hydro Jetting? Hydro jetting is more than just clog removal – it is a pipe cleaning treatment. Our plumbers use pressurized water machines to scour the insides of your pipes. In addition to clearing the drains, hydro jetting removes: ScaleGreaseHairDebrisSoap residueMineral buildupTree root infiltrationPotential water contaminants Commercial Hydro Jetting The pipes at your business or commercial property go through things that home plumbing systems will never experience. Whether you are dealing with large amounts of food waste, runoff from machinery, or other materials that can solidify in the pipeline, we are here for you. Tree roots from the landscaping on the property can also create major issues. We can quickly and effectively find the issue and use water sprayed at an extremely high pressure to restore the inside of the pipe. The hose is connected to a large tank of water and we regulate the water pressure while it scours the pipes. It is essential to hire a knowledgeable plumber, as the amount of water pressure required varies for each job. Older plumbing systems need to be handled with care, while newer, more durable pipes may need extra strength to be cleaned effectively. Do You Need Hydro Jetting or Drain Snaking? If a toy or a wad of tissue is lodged in your toilet, a plumber’s auger may take care of the problem. Similarly, when a kitchen sink is clogged with potato peels or soggy rice, a drain snake can often remove the blockage. We recommend hydro jetting when you are experiencing a consistent issue with your drain. There may be a residual build-up in your pipes or tree roots may be affecting your drainage. We want to provide you with a solution that takes care of your plumbing problems once and for all. If you have a stubborn drain that needs fixing, please contact hydro jetting technician from our family-owned team today! We are always available with 24/7 services. We are proud to serve customers in Los Banos, Turlock, Merced, Patterson, and the surrounding Central Valley areas. What Is Trenchless Technology? Rather than digging a large trench to expose a pipe, trenchless technology allows our service professionals to use lateral techniques in order to address your sewer line repair. There are various methods to employ trenchless technology. The type most often used for homes involves using a hydraulic device attached to one end of the pipe to draw a pipe liner from the other end. With this process, the only digging necessary is to excavate either one or two small holes to access the ends of the pipe. Once the hydraulics have set the pipe liner into place, a device called a pipe burster is pulled through the pipe, causing the pipe liner to expand, and shatter the old pipe. The new pipe liner replaces the old pipe, and our Central Valley service professionals only need to fill in and re-landscape those small holes. Instead of taking days and requiring a huge cleanup, trenchless sewer line replacement or repair only takes a few hours. Contact Our Team Today for This No-Dig Technology Not every plumbing company has the training or the equipment available to them to manage trenchless, “no–dig,” technology to access your sewer line or main water line. with no explanation? Or perhaps you have a damp spot on your carpet and don’t know how it got there. If so, you could very well have a slab leak. This is among the most serious and disheartening plumbing problems that homeowners face. Slab leaks can cause significant damage in a short amount of time if not located and repaired right away. This is why you need a team onsite to perform accurate slab leak detection and repairs as needed. You have that with All American Plumbing Heating & Air. We are “In the Service of Excellence” and have been serving customers throughout Los Banos, Turlock, Merced, Patterson, and the surrounding Central Valley area for over 18 years. Schedule your first appointment by calling our team today at (209) 509-4448 or use our online form. How to tell if you have a slab leak If you notice a sudden spike in your water bill, water pooling in places it shouldn’t, water heater constantly running or even areas of the floor that are suddenly getting hot. You may have a slab leak. Early detection is very important when leaks in your slab’s foundation are in question, as it can save you thousands of dollars in water and home damage. We’ll explain in more detail each one of these signs that you may have a slab leak with the below bullet list, Sudden water bill increase – If you notice your home’s water bill has been higher than normal, this could be due to a leak in your slab foundation. Call our expert slab leak detection & repair for professional help. Water pooling where it shouldn’t – Water will pool under the foundation until it finds a way to escape. Make sure you keep an eye out for any water that seems to be coming out of the slab foundation on the outside of your home. If you don’t have any way for water to pool in that area, AKA, sprinklers, hoses or faucets, you may have a slab leak. Hot water heater always running – When you hot water heater seems to always be running, a slab leak is similar to leaving your hot water faucet on 24/7. If your hot water heater never has hot water, it’s always going to be working non-stop in order to make up for the lost hot water. Floors are suddenly hot – If the slab leak is on the hot water side, eventually the concrete above it will slowly warm up due to the transfer of heat from the leak. Carpet makes it much more difficult to detect, but if you have hardwood flooring or linoleum, you’ll easily find the hot spots from a potential slab leak. What Is a Slab Leak? This is the name given to a leak that occurs beneath the concrete foundation—the slab—of your home. Your home’s foundation helps stabilize your property and protect it against soil erosion, among other issues. Unfortunately, however, you have several plumbing pipes that run under this foundation, and those include your water and sewer lines. Being out of sight means that when one of these pipes springs a leak, you aren’t going to know about it right away. It becomes a slab leak when this leak filters up through the slab of your home, and usually the first visible signs are when damage has already been done. Common Signs That You Have A Slab Leak The signs of slab leaks vary depending on the severity of the leak itself. You might have small suspicions of a slab leak: a higher than usual water bill or an occasional sound of running or dripping water. Or, the signs might be more obvious: standing water surrounding the foundation of your home, cracks on the ceiling or walls, or warm spots in your floor. If you notice any of these common signs that you have a slab leak, act quickly! The longer you let a slab leak go unattended, the worse damage you will experience. Even the smallest leaks can wreak havoc on your home or business. Give All American PHA a call at the first sign of slab leak so we can save you from unnecessary headache (and costs) with quality slab leak repair services. Options For Repairing Slab Leaks What are your options for repairing slab leaks? There isn’t one clear answer to this commonly asked question. The options for repairing slab leaks are entirely dependent on the extent of your slab leak damage. For a single leak, spot repair might be effective – although it is often a temporary fix, and can lead to expensive flooring damage to gain access to the leak source. Most homeowners prefer re-piping or re-routing of plumbing to effectively bypass the slab leak. For this option for repairing slab leaks, new pipes typically made from flexible PEX are routed around the edge of the slab, giving a cost effective solution as well as easy access points for future inspections and repairs. If you’re experiencing multiple pin-hole leaks in your slab, pipe lining is a cost-effective and reliable option. This technique utilizes a thin epoxy coating to cure the lines, effectively sealing off leaks. Repair The Damaged Section Once we have found the source of your slab leak and repair any necessary plumbing, it’s time to tackle the damaged section of slab. Our team at All American PHA is experienced in every phase of slab leak repair – from troubleshooting and finding even the smallest hidden leaks, to repairing the damaged section of slab itself. Don’t attempt a DIY fix! Your slab is a critically important structural element in your home, and repairing it will almost always require professional help. What Causes a Slab Leak? Slab leaks can be caused by a variety of issues. Perhaps the most common causes of slab leaks stem from faulty plumbing systems. Other problems such as soil shifting beneath the slab’s surface, chemical reactions or corrosion, and weak water lines can also lead to slab leaks. Regular inspections and maintenance of your home’s plumbing systems is important to detect the signs of slab leaks before they become major problems. Why Slab Leaks Are Such a Big Deal Slab leaks are significantly worse than other leaks that might occur in your Central Valley area home due to their location. They take a while to notice, making them problematic. Since the leak is located under your home, most people don’t notice them until the problem is visible, as we mentioned above. You may be able to detect a slab leak on your own by watching your water meter after shutting off all your water appliances, but leaks can occur anywhere, and even if you do detect a slab leak, you need to have it professionally addressed. Our team uses special methods to detect slab leaks, such as acoustic listening devices and electronic line locators. This helps us not only to locate the slab leak but to determine the severity of the damage it has caused. Count on Us for Water Heater Installation When researching what water heater is best to purchase, you’ll come across both gas water heaters and electric water heaters. But those aren’t the only options to consider! We know this may be overwhelming, but there’s no need to worry. Our plumbing service professionals are here to help you make an educated decision about what type of water heater is best for you, ensuring that it’s properly sized for your home and that it’s the right style that you want. When you are looking for a water heater, you have two main options: Tank Water Heater: The storage tank water heater is the traditional water heating system you’re likely used to seeing in homes throughout the state. By heating water and keeping a reserve within the tank, you’ll always have hot water when you need it. Tankless Water Heater: The tankless water heater doesn’t store hot water like its counterpart. Rather, it heats only the water needed at any given time. This is why they’re also called “on-demand” water heaters. They’ll never run out of the water! Can Hard Water Hurt My Water Heater? Yes, and this is especially a concern in the Central Valley area. Water hardness is measured in grains—a “normal” amount of hardness would be about 10 grains, but in our community, you can find up to 30 grains of hardness in most homes. The installation of a whole–home water softener will help with this issue, but for an added layer of protection for your water heater, you’d do well to consider a self–cleaning water heater installation. The self-cleaning water heaters that we provide and install will do more than protect against harmful sediment buildup from hard water—it will lengthen the overall lifespan of your water heater, provide a higher ROI than other water heater types, and will offer you better overall operating efficiency as well. Give us a call and our experienced technicians are available to help you. How do I properly maintain a tank type water heater? Like most major home appliances, tank water heaters require regular maintenance to operate at maximum efficiency. If you have a traditional tank type water heater, it is important to uphold a regular maintenance schedule to extend your water heater’s lifespan. To properly maintain a tank type water heater, the following steps should be taken at least once per year: Test the pressure relief valve and replace it if necessary. (You will need to replace the valve if water doesn’t drain when you lift the lever.)Drain sediment. Tank water heaters often fall victim to sediment buildup on the bottom of the tank. To properly maintain your tank water heater, this sediment needs to be removed annually, or more depending on use. Using a bucket, let the water flow from the drain valve until the water runs clear of sediment. (This usually takes approximately 2-3 gallons of water.) Be careful, as the water draining from the valve will be hot! Check the temperature setting. Be sure the water heater’s dial is set to 120ªF. Temperatures higher than 120º can lead to injury (scalding) and increase buildup of residue and sediment in the tank. Are tank type heaters less efficient than tankless water heaters? Tankless water heaters are typically more efficient than tank type heaters, although new tank heaters have made improvements in the efficiency department in comparison to models of years past. Exactly how much more efficient a tankless water heater is than a tank type heater depends on the amount of hot water you use in your home. According to Energy.gov, “for homes that use 41 gallons or less of hot water daily, demand (or tankless) water heaters can be 24% to 34% more energy efficient than conventional storage tank water heaters.” When Is It Time for a New Water Heater? Do you have an older water heater—15+ years of age—that is sucking up your home’s energy when heating water? Or did your storage tank water heater give out on you and flood the basement or garage? We hope not—but if either of these things occurred then it’s certainly time for a water heater replacement! This is especially true for storage tank water heaters, which require the replacement of the anode rod every few years or so. The anode rod is the component of your water heater tank that absorbs rust and corrosion so that the lining of your water heater won’t. To reduce the chance of running into water heater problems, be sure to schedule maintenance with our team on an annual basis. The use of forced-air heating systems such as furnaces and heat pumps is widespread throughout the Central Valley area. However, they are not the only option for whole home heating. Hydronic boiler systems have grown in popularity recently due to their efficiency, clean operation, and the fact that they allow for efficient floor and baseboard heating. Like all heating systems, however, boilers can only work as effectively and efficiently as they’re meant to if they are professionally installed by a team of service professionals with extensive training and experience. You have that with our boiler repair experts. Schedule your first appointment by calling our team today at (209) 509-4448 or use our online form. We are proud to serve customers in Los Banos, Turlock, Merced, Patterson, and the surrounding Central Valley areas. How Does a Boiler Work? Hydronic boiler systems function by heating water to a temperature between 120–140°F, then distributing that water through a series of pipes in your home. These pipes feed into either baseboard heaters, floorboards, radiators, or some combination of all three. What makes this process more efficient than forced-air heating is that the heat dissipates slowly and spreads evenly throughout your home. Boilers also help with any air quality problems you may be experiencing in the home, which we’ll get to below. Your air quality can be supplemented, too, with the right air purifier and humidity balancing system. Expert Boiler Installation There are several advantages to having a boiler system professionally installed in your home. Furnaces, while incredibly effective and efficient these days, simply cannot offer you everything a boiler can, such as: Longevity: Boilers have a reputation for long service lives. This is because they have very few mechanical moving parts and therefore do not wear down as fast over time. Fewer repairs: Since there are fewer moving parts, this also means there is less of a need for boiler repairs over the years. Efficiency: Water serves as a better heat transfer method than air, so a boiler can heat your home faster and more efficiently than other systems. Better indoor air quality: Forced-air systems use ductwork, where dust and debris can gather, to be dispersed through your home. The radiant power of a boiler is clean, eliminating air quality problems. Your household will be affected by far fewer contaminants and allergens, creating a healthier environment for your entire family. Boiler Replacement Services While boilers typically have a long lifespan, they will – like most things – eventually reach a limit. If you have an existing boiler that has seen better days and is beyond repair, All American Plumbing Heating & Air can help with boiler replacement services. When replacing your boiler, it’s important to turn to a licensed team you can trust. We will help you find the right replacement boiler for your heating needs and install it quickly and affordably. In addition, we’ll provide you with a recommended maintenance schedule to keep your boiler replacement unit running efficiently and effectively for years to come. Emergency Boiler Repair While boilers don’t have as many moving parts as the traditional furnace, they are not invincible. Every so often, homeowners will find themselves in need of emergency boiler repair. Because of the way boilers work (distributing hot water through pipes in the home), damage to these systems can be extremely problematic. At All American Plumbing Heating & Air, we understand that time is of the essence when it comes to emergency boiler repair, which is why we are on standby accepting calls 24/7 for our customers in need. We Offer Boiler Repair & Maintenance Boilers might not need as many repair services as the average forced-air heater, but they are not invulnerable. At some point during your boiler’s lifespan, you may need to call a heating service professional to fix a leak, find the source of an odd noise, or restore heating power. Fortunately, you needn’t look far for trained and licensed heating technicians who are available 24/7 for all your heating repair needs. They receive warm or cool air in a single centralized unit that distributes that air through a series of air ducts via a fan. The key difference between a ductless air conditioning and heating system and a central AC or furnace is their decentralized nature. Rather than a single indoor unit, each room or zone of your home has its own individual blower unit. Whether you’re using ductless systems for heating or even ductless air conditioning, the system lets you control the temperature in each room separately. This set up allows for a fine level of control that you simply can’t get with a centralized unit. More importantly, you can turn off the air or heat in parts of your home that aren’t being used at the moment, which lowers the strain on the system and reduces your monthly bills in the meantime. Our trained and experienced team believes “In the Service of Excellence” and we’ll help you find the right match for your home, providing installation, repair, and maintenance for your ductless system. Can All Homes Benefit from Going with our Ductless systems? There are a variety of home types throughout the Central Valley, each with their own specific needs. It’s up to you as the homeowner to make that call, but we can certainly help you make an informed decision. At All American Plumbing Heating & Air, we tend to steer our customers with smaller homes towards more centralized systems, as the benefits of going ductless are often lost on homes with less square footage. But if you have a home with a lot of space or multiple rooms, then a ductless system can certainly help you contain your cooling and heating energy, and therefore your cooling and heating costs. climate control system that combines the power of a central air conditioner with the effectiveness of an electrically powered heating system. How Heat Pumps Both Cool & Heat The innovative technology of a heat pump isn’t that it is two different systems packaged into one unit. It is actually a single system that operatesf in such a way that it can bring heat into the home while in heating mode, or remove heat from the home while in cooling mode. All it takes is an adjustment on the thermostat to activate the reversing valve to use this system year–round. But how does this all work? Well, a heat pump is an air conditioning system, essentially. But it can change the direction it works. A standard AC system circulates refrigerant in order to absorb heat along the indoor coil and then releases it through the outdoor coil. The reversing valve we mentioned above is responsible for changing the direction that refrigerant flows, causing the two coils to swap functions. Now, heat is absorbed along the outdoor coil and released through the indoor coil. We Provide Heat Pump Installation Services If you’re still on the fence about whether or not a heat pump is a good investment for your home, we urge you to consider these advantages: Year-Round Use: This is perhaps the biggest benefit. A heat pump saves you space, as you don’t have the indoor unit of an AC and a furnace to contend with. It also saves you money. Efficiency: Heat pumps are far more efficient in heating mode than other electrical systems. This is because heat pumps use electricity to transfer heat from one area to another, versus generating it through electrical resistance. Safety: Today’s heaters are built with safety in mind. However, when you use natural gas or another type of heating fuel, there is always an inherent risk that you simply do not have to worry about with a heat pump system. Quality Heat Pump Repairs & Maintenance If your heat pump struggles to heat or to cool, or it becomes stuck in one mode or starts making concerning noises, you can reach out to All American Plumbing Heating & Air at your convenience, 24/7, for heat pump repair services. What benefits does a heat pump provide? Heat pumps transfer heat from one place to another by using evaporation and condensation of a refrigerant that cycles between an indoor and an outdoor unit. We are proud to serve customers in Los Banos, Turlock, Merced, Patterson, and the surrounding Central Valley areas. What Is Radiant Heating? Radiant heating is a type of whole-home heating system that you may have heard referred to as “in-floor heating.” This type of heating method warms your home from the ground up, using tubes or coils installed in your flooring. These tubes and coils are then heated using either water or electricity. The benefits of radiant heating include: More consistent heating throughout the home, and fewer cold spotsLower energy bills than with forced-air systems as radiant heat systems use less electricityReduction of dust and germs in your home’s airBetter overall air quality than seen with forced-air systemsReduced wear and tear of the system as radiant heat systems are protected by your flooring Radiant heating requires professional installation, and it is recommended that you work with HVAC technicians whom you trust and who have extensive experience installing and repairing these types of systems, like ours at All American Plumbing, Heating & Air. The refrigerant-based air conditioning system is the one that most homeowners think of and the one that most depend on. The central air conditioner is a very effective means of cooling down your Central Valley area home, but it’s not the only method. In the right home, there is an alternative that can help lower energy costs drastically. One alternative that All American Plumbing Heating & Air installs and services is the evaporative cooler also referred to as a swamp cooler. Schedule your first appointment by calling our team today at (209) 509-4448 or use our online form. We are proud to serve customers in Los Banos, Turlock, Merced, Patterson, and the surrounding Central Valley areas. How Are Swamp Coolers Different? You may be wondering what it is exactly that a swamp cooler does. The simple explanation is that it uses water to cool down the air entering your home. The standard centralized AC uses refrigerant to remove heat from your indoor air and turn it into cool air that comes back through your vents. There is no chemical refrigerant in an evaporative cooler or swamp cooler, however. Rather, the system uses dampened pads that are kept wet through the action of pumps. A fan pulls in outside air and as the warm air moves over the pads, it loses heat to the water—much like the breeze you feel coming off a large body of water such as a lake. The Benefits of Evaporative Cooling The primary advantage of evaporative cooling is that these systems cost less to run than more traditional air conditioning system types. Running your evaporative cooler requires powering the fans and the pumps, which consumes less electricity than running the compressor in a central AC. If your home is well suited for an evaporative cooler, it can substitute a standard AC on many days, and lower your energy costs. Another great benefit of evaporative cooling is that it helps combat dry conditions, which we get our fair share of in the surrounding Central Valley communities. The moisture from the pads enters the air and helps raise the humidity level, increasing your home comfort on dry summer days. Call Us for Evaporative Cooling experts It bears mentioning that evaporative coolers are not the right solution for every home. To make sure that installing one of these systems is the best way to lower your energy costs and not raise your humidity levels too much, you should reach out to our experienced service professionals. If we don’t feel an evaporative cooler will benefit you, we’ll be honest, and we’ll make recommendations for other types of cooling systems that could be a better match. Backflow Testing and Prevention Services in Los Banos, Turlock, Patterson and Merced Providing Upfront Pricing to Fit Every Budget Keeping your commercial property’s water clean and safe is a priority, and one way you do this is through the installation and maintenance of a backflow prevention device. Furthermore, if you have a commercial property, backflow prevention is required by law. Our commercial plumbers are all fully trained and certified and can help you ensure that your backflow prevention device is functioning correctly. We can also handle any backflow repair or replacement projects. Schedule your first appointment by calling our team today at (209) 509-4448 or use our online form. We are proud to serve customers in Los Banos, Turlock, Merced, Patterson, and the surrounding Central Valley areas. What is Backflow? The water going in and out of your business flows through the system in one direction only. Your plumbing brings fresh water into your property from its municipal source, and your sewer line removes wastewater. However, when the pressure in the system drops or changes, backflow can occur, and sewage from your sewer line can flow back into your plumbing, contaminating your fresh water supply. If left unchecked, backflow can endanger the water supply going to other homes and businesses in the area as well, creating a severe problem, leaving you potentially liable. A fully functioning backflow prevention device reduces the likelihood of this happening and automatically stops backflow from contaminating the water supply. Call our Backflow prevention experts. Our plumbers can help you with any backflow-related issues, including: Mandatory backflow testing Installation of new or replacement backflow prevention devices Backflow preventer repair jobs Routine plumbing system checks through our AMP maintenance club We Are Always Available & Affordable At All American Plumbing, Heating & Air, we know how costly plumbing repairs and installations can be. We are committed to providing our customers with honest advice, upfront pricing, and a 100% satisfaction guarantee. Our customer service representatives are always available, day or night; when you call us, you never get an answering service. We are founded on the tenets of character, honor, integrity, and trust. How often should a backflow preventer be tested? A backflow preventer is an essential device that works to keep your home’s water flowing in one direction. Without it, your water may become contaminated and unsafe. Because of the seriousness in nature of a failing backflow preventer, it is important to have the device inspected annually. Backflow preventers may break down because of an accumulation of debris, damage, or the age of the unit. It only takes an hour or less to do the testing and it is worth it in the long run. When it comes time to schedule your yearly test, call us. We serve Los Banos, Turlock, Patterson and Merced and we can help! Commercial Indoor Air Quality Testing and Services in Los Banos, Turlock, Patterson and Merced Let Our HVAC Technicians Keep Your Company Breathing Easier At ALL AMERICAN PLUMBING HEATING & AIR, we understand how essential it is for commercial property and business owners to keep their properties consistently comfortable. We also believe that to achieve this, you need to do more than just maintain comfortable temperatures. The quality of air that your tenants, customers, and employees enjoy is just as important to overall comfort. Especially considering that without the right products and services, that indoor air quality can actually be worse than outdoor air quality. Our indoor air quality team is proud to provide our outstanding commercial indoor air quality products and services throughout the Central Valley. Contact us today to start improving your indoor air quality and to learn how we live by our motto of “In the Service of Excellence.” Schedule your first appointment by calling our team today at (209) 509-4448 or use our online form. We are proud to serve customers in Los Banos, Turlock, Merced, Patterson, and the surrounding Central Valley areas. How to Improve Your Commercial Indoor Air Quality There are many factors that can affect the quality of your indoor air. Temperature is just the beginning. There might be unhealthy contaminants in the air, or it may be too humid or dry in the space. Whatever the problem is, we have the product to resolve it. We can help you to install or service a variety of air quality systems, including: Air Filtration Systems: The air filter that comes standard with commercial HVAC systems is there to protect the inside components of those systems, not your property’s indoor air. For that, you need a specialized commercial air filtration system. Air Purifiers: Depending on the nature of your business or commercial space, you could have a number of contaminants present in the air, from VOCs (Volatile Organic Compounds) and viruses to allergens and mold spores. Let us help match the right air purifier to your specific needs. Humidity Balancing: Unless you’re a fairly new California resident, you likely already know what a challenge it can be to maintain comfort when it gets dry in the winter and humid in the summer. Fortunately, we provide quality humidifiers and dehumidifiers for commercial spaces. ERVs and HRVs: The way buildings are constructed nowadays allows for the most efficient use of your HVAC systems possible. This is great news for your commercial heating and cooling bills, but not so much for your indoor air quality. This tight construction can leave the air feeling stale and uncomfortable. Improve the comfort of all your property’s occupants with the right energy recovery or heat recovery ventilator! What Causes Poor Indoor Air Quality? There are a number of reasons that the indoor air quality in your commercial space might be poor. A major factor is what that space is used for. Restaurants and commercial kitchens, for instance, might have poor indoor air quality due to insufficient ventilation above the ovens, ranges, and other cooking appliances. If you own or manage a business or even a housing complex, then the individual actions of employees and residents can have a major impact on indoor air quality. Reach out to our indoor air quality specialists at (209) 509-4448 to schedule service! Commercial Water Heater Installation, Repair Services in Los Banos, Turlock, Patterson and Merced 24/7 Emergency Services Available There probably isn’t a single plumbing appliance in your commercial space that you would want to go without for an extended period of time. There is no exception for the water heater, which gets used on a daily, even hourly, basis. Commercial water heaters are a vital part of the buildings in which they’re installed. To get the most out of yours, you want to trust only trained professionals for their installation and service. ALL AMERICAN PLUMBING, HEATING & AIR installs, repairs, and maintains commercial water heaters for businesses and properties throughout the Central Valley. If you need reliable commercial water heater services in Turlock, contact our team today at (209) 509-4448 to schedule an appointment. Let Us Handle Your Commercial Water Heater Installation There’s no better way to start off with a fully efficient and effective commercial water heater that will serve you for years to come than by scheduling your installation with a trained and experienced team of professional commercial plumbers. We provide comprehensive commercial water heater installation services to ensure that your system gets off to a great start. If you need multiple systems thanks to a large space, we’ll work with you on that, too. We’ll ensure you’re matched up with the right type of commercial water heater, in addition to the right size. Do You Need Commercial Water Heater Services? When your commercial water heater is properly inspected and maintained, it will last a long time. However, no system lasts forever, and you may eventually need repairs or even a replacement. There are several symptoms to look out for that may indicate that it is time to repair or replace your water heater: Low Output: Not being able to meet your moderate demand levels is not a good sign when it comes to commercial water heaters. Reach out to our team today if yours are struggling to provide your commercial space with enough hot water. Leaks: A leaking water heater is never a good sign. You’ll want to have one of our commercial plumbers come take a look right away to ensure that corrosion hasn’t gotten to the system, and to repair the issue at hand. High Repair Frequency: This is a case in which replacement would probably be the best option. All systems develop problems every now and then. But you should not need to call for commercial water heater repairs every few months. Chances are, it’s far more economically beneficial to replace the system if you find this is the case. Old Age: Commercial water heaters today are designed in such a way that they can last up to two decades—so long as they are well maintained. After that point, water heaters start to lose efficiency and become more expensive to run and maintain, putting a strain on your budget and bottom line. Comprehensive Commercial Water Heater Maintenance Professionally installed water heaters can last a long time, but only if they are properly maintained. There is no exception for commercial systems. In fact, commercial plumbing systems need maintenance even more than residential systems, considering what’s at stake if a commercial system fails. If and when your commercial water heater develops a problem, we’re here to help, 24/7. But we would like to help your business or commercial space avoid the costliest of repairs by helping you schedule check-ups through our AMP CLUB MAINTENANCE PLAN. Commercial Tankless Water Heater You may be familiar with the benefits of residential tankless water heaters like how they are fast, efficient and eco-friendly. Many people ask us, “are tankless water heaters good for commercial use?” Yes! In general, tankless water heaters can work just as well as traditional water heaters for a restaurant or other commercial facility. A commercial tankless water heater will provide the benefits of increased efficiency, energy savings and cost reductions that residential tankless models are expected to provide. If you are in the Los Banos, Turlock, Patterson, and Merced areas call All American Plumbing, Heating & Air and ask about commercial tankless water heaters to see if one will be right for you! Call our commercial water heater experts today at (209) 509-4448 to schedule your appointment.
